# Larynx

> The larynx is a **cartilaginous valve** in the anterior neck at C3–C6, situated between the [[Oral Cavity]] / pharynx above and the trachea below. It serves three functions: **airway protection** during swallowing, **phonation** (voice production), and **respiration**.

## 🔗 Key Connections
- [[Digestive System]] / [[00 - AnatomyLink Home]]
- Above: Pharynx (oropharynx/hypopharynx) → [[Oral Cavity]]
- Below: Trachea → Bronchi → Lungs
- Anterior: Strap muscles of neck, thyroid gland
- Skeletal relations: [[Cervical Vertebrae]] (C3–C6 level), [[Mandible]] (hyoid bone above)
- Blood supply: Superior laryngeal artery (from superior thyroid → external carotid); inferior laryngeal artery (from inferior thyroid → subclavian)
- Innervation: **Vagus nerve (CN X)** — Superior laryngeal nerve (sensory above cords; cricothyroid motor); **Recurrent laryngeal nerve (RLN)** — all other intrinsic muscles + sensory below cords

## 🔬 Cartilages

| Cartilage | Type | Function |
|-----------|------|----------|
| **Thyroid** | Hyaline | Largest; "Adam's apple"; protects cords anteriorly |
| **Cricoid** | Hyaline | Only complete ring in airway; base of larynx |
| **Epiglottis** | Elastic | Leaf-shaped; folds over larynx during swallowing |
| **Arytenoids** (×2) | Hyaline | Pivot; open/close vocal cords |
| Corniculate (×2) | Elastic | On apex of arytenoids |
| Cuneiform (×2) | Elastic | In aryepiglottic folds |

## 🔬 Interior Spaces

| Space | Description |
|-------|-------------|
| Vestibule | Above vestibular folds (false cords) |
| Sinus (ventricle) | Between vestibular and vocal folds |
| **Rima glottidis** | Opening between true vocal cords; narrowest point in adult airway |
| Infraglottic space | Below vocal cords → trachea |

## ⚙️ Function
- **Airway protection** — epiglottis + arytenoids close rima glottidis during swallowing; cough reflex
- **Phonation** — air vibrates vocal cords; pitch ↑ with tension (cricothyroid muscle lengthens/tenses cords); loudness ↑ with airflow
- **Valsalva manoeuvre** — glottis closes to increase intra-abdominal pressure (defecation, childbirth, lifting)

## 🏥 Clinical Significance
- **Recurrent laryngeal nerve (RLN) palsy** — hoarseness; risk in thyroid surgery, neck dissection, aortic arch aneurysm (left RLN loops around aorta)
- **Croup (laryngotracheobronchitis)** — viral (parainfluenza); subglottic oedema; barking cough + stridor in children
- **Epiglottitis** — bacterial (*H. influenzae* type b); swollen "cherry-red" epiglottis; airway emergency
- **Laryngeal cancer** — squamous cell carcinoma; smoking/alcohol; glottic (best prognosis — hoarseness early) vs. supraglottic
- **Cricothyrotomy** — emergency airway through cricothyroid membrane (between thyroid and cricoid cartilages)
- **Intubation landmark** — vocal cords visible during laryngoscopy; ETT passes through rima glottidis

